720016f-a.text:
Gold Street, south from (No. 23, right), a point midway between John and Platt Streets, aoross the latter to Maiden Lane. The 4-story corner structure seen on the right and bearing a "Cafe" sign is the "Jack Knife" Building (No. 19); a triangular structure that is a remmnant of a larger building, part of which was demolished when Jacob Platt cut Platt Street through in 1834. Past same, and occupying the S.W. corner is a 4-story structure (white) No. 15, that has been occupied by Thomas Prosser and Son since 1845. This firm, the American representatives of the Krupp Steel Works of Germany will move to 120 Wall Street, according to the
New York Times of December 8, 1937.
About 1910.
Brown Brothers.
720016f-a.folder: Gold Street & John Street, Manhattan, NY

720702f-b.text:
(1)
91 to 101 John Street, (97-101 only partly shown) north side, east from and including Gold (left), to, but not including Cliff Streets. These houses were later raned to make room for the 25-story Insurance Company of North America Building. Also shown is exoavation work in progress (south side of the Street) on the foundation for the new 28-story office building, No. 90
John Street.
October 13, 1930.
P. L. Sperr.
(2)
A portion of the same, showing No's. 91 and 93 only. Also seen, prominently, is the 14-story National Underwriters Building, at the N. W. corner of Gold Street. At the extreme left appears a portion of the 25story Insurance Centre Building, at the S. W. corner of the latter Street.
October 13, 1930.
P. L. Sperr.
(3)
A part of the same, showing No's. 95 and 97-101 completely. No. 97-101 is at the N.W. corner of Cliff Street and bears No's. 1-13 on the
latter Street.
October 13, 1930.
P. L. Sperr.
